rComments: Professor Gress is both a great mentor and conductor. While he comes across as angry, he is deeply passionate about the musicianship of the students and their growth as performers. Proper preparation is needed to survive this course. Also he has a sense of humor and wit that are razor sharp!

I studied under this prof for two years in two different classes. His attention to detail and use of rehearsal time was excellent. He cares about his work and wants his students to as well. If you lack attention to detail and good work habits you will be very aware of this after being a member of his class. This is useful.

Not a good conductor or prof. Uses embarassment as a teaching tool, but he has hissy fits over nothing and would rather talk about what pieces he played when he was in high school rather than discussing something relevant about the piece. Picks favourites and sticks with them, not inspiring. Not a failed musician, a failed prof.

A great prof. Doesn't tolerate slacking and people who are unprepared. Likes dissonant music, which is usually fin but can get tiresome. Will single you out if you haven't learned your part. Very musical and inspiring!
Great conductor, the repetoire contains a lot of marches but they are usually pretty easy. Make sure you are prepared for class, he is not afrain to single people out and make them play alone.
